INTRODUCTION¶

The Ford GoBike dataset provides a comprehensive overview of bike-sharing activities within a specified timeframe. With a total of 16 columns and over 183,000 rows, this dataset encapsulates crucial information about bike trips, including duration, start and end times, station locations, user demographics, and bike share status. Analyzing this dataset can unveil valuable insights into urban mobility patterns, user behaviors, and operational dynamics, informing strategic decision-making for bike-sharing programs and urban transportation planning initiatives.

  • The columns include the following

duration_sec: This column represents the duration of each bike trip in seconds. It indicates how long each trip lasted from start to finish.

start_time: This column denotes the start time of each bike trip. It provides information on when the trip commenced, including the date and time.

end_time: This column indicates the end time of each bike trip. It specifies when the trip concluded, including the date and time.

start_station_id: This column contains the unique identifier for the starting station of each bike trip. It helps identify the specific station where the bike trip originated.

start_station_name: This column provides the name or description of the starting station for each bike trip. It offers additional context about the location where the trip began.

start_station_latitude: This column denotes the latitude coordinates of the starting station. It specifies the geographic location of the station in terms of its north-south position.

start_station_longitude: This column represents the longitude coordinates of the starting station. It specifies the geographic location of the station in terms of its east-west position.

end_station_id: This column contains the unique identifier for the ending station of each bike trip. It helps identify the specific station where the bike trip concluded.

end_station_name: This column provides the name or description of the ending station for each bike trip. It offers additional context about the location where the trip ended.

end_station_latitude: This column denotes the latitude coordinates of the ending station. It specifies the geographic location of the station where the trip concluded in terms of its north-south position.

end_station_longitude: This column represents the longitude coordinates of the ending station. It specifies the geographic location of the station where the trip concluded in terms of its east-west position.

bike_id: This column contains the unique identifier for each bike used in the bike-sharing program. It helps track individual bikes and their usage over time.

user_type: This column indicates the type of user who took the bike trip, such as a subscriber or customer. It categorizes users based on their subscription status.

member_birth_year: This column represents the birth year of the bike trip user. It provides information about the age of the user, which can be derived from their birth year.

member_gender: This column denotes the gender of the bike trip user. It categorizes users based on their gender identity, such as male, female, or other.

bike_share_for_all_trip: This column indicates whether the bike trip was shared for all or part of the journey as part of a bike-sharing program. It provides information on the bike-sharing status of the trip.

TIME SERIES ANALYSIS¶

In [31]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Convert start_time to datetime and set it as the index
Bike['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(Bike['start_time'])
Bike.set_index('start_time', inplace=True)

# Resample the data to daily frequency and calculate the number of trips for each day
daily_usage = Bike.resample('D').size()

# Plot the daily bike usage trend
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
daily_usage.plot(color='skyblue')
plt.title('Daily Bike Usage Trend')
plt.xlabel('Date')
plt.ylabel('Number of Trips')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()
In [32]:
# Resample the data to weekly frequency and calculate the number of trips for each week
weekly_usage = Bike.resample('W').size()

# Plot the weekly bike usage trend
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
weekly_usage.plot(color='skyblue')
plt.title('Weekly Bike Usage Trend')
plt.xlabel('Week')
plt.ylabel('Number of Trips')
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Analysis¶

Is there a correlation between user age and trip duration?¶

In [33]:
# Remove rows with missing values in 'member_birth_year' or 'duration_sec'
Bike_cleaned = Bike.dropna(subset=['member_birth_year', 'duration_sec']).copy()  # Make a copy to avoid modifying the original DataFrame
In [34]:
# Calculate user age from 'member_birth_year' (assuming current year is 2024)
current_year = 2024
Bike_cleaned['user_age'] = current_year - Bike_cleaned['member_birth_year']
In [35]:
# Calculate the correlation coefficient between user age and trip duration
correlation_coefficient = np.corrcoef(Bike_cleaned['user_age'], Bike_cleaned['duration_sec'])[0, 1]

print('Correlation Coefficient between User Age and Trip Duration:', correlation_coefficient)

Correlation Coefficient between User Age and Trip Duration: 0.006026742656500281
